An unprecedented future
JERUSALEM – With my nearly 90 years of life, I cannot remember a time when the past was so irrelevant for political decision-making.
No significant developments of the present were predicted by anyone.
Experts did study the past, but due to their entrapment in old paradigms, they could not derive the future from it.
Due to the dynamic complexity of today's world, where events are more interdependent given the scientifically grounded and rapidly changing global economy, we are unable to predict the future based on a linear extrapolation of the past.
The only certainty is that the future will be determined by scientific progress and innovation, which cannot be known in advance.
As a result of these developments, traditional state power and that of leaders is diminishing. In today's globalized economy, it is not politicians but innovators who exert the greatest influence.
The globalized economy affects all states, yet no single state can determine its outcome because science and technology know no bounds.
Global businesses want to pursue their operations worldwide, which on one hand undermines sovereignty, but on the other hand weakens racism and prejudice, as well as nationalism significantly.
Owing to this change, the fate of this world now lies in the hands of a younger generation. They are more technologically adept than their parents and connected to each other through social networks that transcend national borders, language barriers, or different forms of government.
The young founders of Facebook and Google exert greater global influence than many heads of state and generals.
These young people also form the vanguard of emerging political protest movements.
The "Arab Spring," the tent demonstrations in Israel, Occupy Wall Street, and the protests in Russia do not mark a clash of cultures but a battle of generations.
The younger generation knows that the way states and economies are currently being run is unsuitable for the new times.
But there are political "free riders" who want to exploit this recent awakening. However, they do not aim to further develop an agenda of freedom, but to introduce new forms of coercion.
In the Arab world, it is primarily Islamist extremists who take over the protests of the young generation and steal their revolution.
Israel has positively responded to the will of the young generation, but should not intervene in the events of the Arab world.
We stand at heart with the rebelling youths and their legitimate desire for freedom and human rights, which should enable them to make their voices heard, choose their political leadership, and earn a living.
The Israelis are waiting for the day when their country is no longer the only democracy in the region, because existing as an island of prosperity amidst a sea of poverty is unnatural.
However, there is serious concern that politically well-organized extremists will try to win control over less organized liberals in elections and thus prevent peace and stability.
Radical fundamentalists cannot offer real solutions to the fundamental problems of the region.
The current social upheavals threaten their way of life, which includes discrimination against women and a ban on modern education.
However, only fundamental reforms of established authority can pave the way towards freedom and growth.
Israel can serve as an example for others in achieving economic prosperity and social freedom, since its success lies in the fact that the country started with virtually nothing.
Upon our return home, we were rich in history but poor in natural resources.
We could only rely on our human capital.
Therefore, we invested in education and science. That is why we have the highest percentage of scientists and patents per capita today.
About 95 percent of our agriculture is based on high technology.
We use less water and still have higher yield per square meter of cultivated land than any other country in the world.
What Israel achieves, others can also achieve.
We are happy to offer our help wherever it is desired.
Together and in peace with our neighbors, we can shape a region of hope, development, and success.
Most importantly, we must do everything in our power to end the conflict with the Palestinians.
Israel was not created to rule over another people, and this is not Israel's destiny.
We are genuinely interested in creating a Palestinian state that exists peacefully and side by side with Israel – the democratic state of the Jewish people.
For us, peace is both a moral imperative and a national security strategy, because the resolution of the conflict would help stabilize the region by neutralizing the extremists who seek to manipulate citizen movements to advance their radical agenda.
The international community can support these efforts by incentivizing those countries that strive for freedom and progress.
At the same time, decisive and groundbreaking political measures against the extremists must be taken.
Especially Iran is a source of moral degradation, where it fuels extremism and blocks reforms. It crushes legitimate protests by its own citizens and works against the brave Syrians who are currently fighting for their freedom.
Moreover, Iran uses several proxies to incite terror against moderate forces in the Palestinian Authority, Lebanon, and Iraq.
If Iran succeeds in acquiring nuclear weapons, the leaders of the country could shock the Near and Middle East and incite even more extremism and violence.
Israel will defend itself if Iran continues to demand the destruction of Israel.
But Israel is not the only one at risk. Iran is a threat to peace and stability worldwide.
The democracies of the world have declared that they will not allow Iran to acquire nuclear weapons. It is their duty to fulfill this commitment before it becomes impossible.
Beyond these short-term challenges, we all have the duty to fundamentally change how we prepare our children to deal with the world of today.
At a time when the past has become irrelevant for predicting the future, education must offer all children the opportunity to realize their potential.
Today's teachers should inspire our children to creativity and innovation.
Self-realization is just as important as free expression of opinion.
I write this article at 88 years old, but not because I have learned from experience.
On the contrary: experience is overvalued and often restricts the courage needed to face the future and create an unprecedented new world.
The future is already here. Looking back makes no sense.
